  "prompt": "What does white smoke from motorcycle exhaust mean?",
  "response": "White smoke from a motorcycle exhaust can indicate several potential issues, depending on the color, consistency, and circumstances under which it appears. Here are the most common causes:\n\n### 1. **Condensation (Normal in Cold Weather)**  \n   - If the smoke is thin and dissipates quickly, it could simply be condensation burning off in the exhaust system. This is common in cold or humid weather and is not a cause for concern.\n\n### 2. **Coolant Leak (Internal Engine Issue)**  \n   - Thick, persistent white smoke often indicates that coolant is entering the combustion chamber. This could be due to:  \n     - A blown head gasket.  \n     - A cracked cylinder head or engine block.  \n     - A damaged or warped cylinder head.  \n   - The smoke may have a sweet smell due to the antifreeze in the coolant.\n\n### 3. **Water in the Fuel System**  \n   - If water has contaminated the fuel, it can vaporize and produce white smoke when burned. This can happen if the fuel tank or fuel line has been exposed to moisture.\n\n### 4. **Transmission Oil in the Combustion Chamber (For 2-Stroke Engines)**  \n   - In 2-stroke motorcycles, excessive transmission oil can enter the combustion chamber due to a faulty crankshaft seal, resulting in white smoke.\n\n### 5. **Incorrect Air-Fuel Mixture**  \n   - An overly rich air-fuel mixture (too much fuel) can cause incomplete combustion, leading to white or grayish smoke.\n\n### 6. **Diesel or Contaminated Fuel**  \n   - If diesel or another contaminant has been added to the fuel, it can produce white smoke when burned.\n\n### What to Do:  \n- If the smoke is persistent and thick, it\u2019s important to inspect the motorcycle immediately.  \n- Check the coolant level and look for signs of leakage.  \n- Inspect the oil for a milky appearance, which could indicate coolant mixing with the oil.  \n- Consult a mechanic to diagnose and repair the issue, especially if it involves internal engine problems.  \n\nIgnoring white smoke can lead to severe engine damage, so timely diagnosis and repair are crucial.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
